        "displayMode": "gradient"
      },
      "description": "**Bar gauge** showing the latest per-core CPU usage.\n\nSorted by core ID. Green < 70%, Yellow 70-90%, Red > 90%.\n\nIf one core is pegged at 100% \u2014 find the single-threaded process using `perf top` or `pidstat -u 1`."
    },
    {
      "title": "\ud83d\uddfa\ufe0f Process \u2192 Core Mapping (which process is on which core)",
      "type": "timeseries",
      "datasource": {
        "type": "prometheus",
        "uid": "${DS_PROMETHEUS}"
      },
      "targets": [
        {
          "expr": "bcm_process_core_map",
          "legendFormat": "{{process}} \u2192 Core {{core}}",
          "datasource": {
            "type": "prometheus",
            "uid": "${DS_PROMETHEUS}"
          }
        }
      ],
      "gridPos": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 22,
        "w": 16,
        "h": 8
      },
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {
          "unit": "percent",
          "thresholds": {
            "mode": "absolute",
            "steps": [
              {
                "color": "green",
                "value": null
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        "overrides": []
      },
      "options": {
        "legend": {
          "displayMode": "table",
          "placement": "bottom",
          "calcs": [
            "min",
            "max",
            "mean",
            "lastNotNull"
          ]
        }
      },
      "description": "**How it's calculated:**\n\n`ps -eo pid,comm,%cpu,psr` \u2014 the PSR column is the **processor** (core) that the process last executed on.\n\n**Linux Kernel Source:**\n- PSR = `/proc/[pid]/stat` field 39 (`processor`)\n- This is the core number where the task was last scheduled by the CFS\n- Updated every context switch when the scheduler picks a core via `select_task_rq_fair()`\n\n**How to read this panel:**\n- Each line = one process, plotted by CPU% over time\n- Legend shows `process \u2192 Core N` \u2014 which core it's currently on\n- If a process jumps between cores \u2192 not pinned (normal CFS behavior)\n- If a process stays on one core \u2192 either pinned via `taskset` or CPU affinity\n\n**CPU Affinity:**\n- `taskset -p <pid>` shows the affinity mask\n- Weka pins I/O threads to specific cores via `cpuset`\n- Processes without explicit pinning can migrate between cores freely\n- The scheduler moves tasks to balance load across NUMA nodes"
    },
    {
      "title": "\ud83d\udcca Processes Per Core (load distribution)",
      "type": "bargauge",
      "datasource": {
        "type": "prometheus",
        "uid": "${DS_PROMETHEUS}"
      },
      "targets": [
        {
          "expr": "bcm_core_process_count",
          "legendFormat": "Core {{core}}",
          "datasource": {
            "type": "prometheus",
            "uid": "${DS_PROMETHEUS}"
          },
          "instant": true,
          "range": false
        }
      ],
      "gridPos": {
        "x": 16,
        "y": 22,
        "w": 8,
        "h": 8
      },
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {
          "unit": "",
          "thresholds": {
            "mode": "absolute",
            "steps": [
              {
                "color": "green",
                "value": null
              },
              {
                "color": "#EAB839",
                "value": 30
              },
              {
                "color": "red",
                "value": 50
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        "overrides": []
      },
      "options": {
        "reduceOptions": {
          "calcs": [
            "lastNotNull"
          ],
          "fields": "",
          "values": false
        },
        "orientation": "horizontal",
        "displayMode": "gradient"
      },
      "description": "**How it's calculated:**\n\nCount of userspace processes assigned to each core from `ps -eo psr`.\n\n**What this tells you:**\n- Even distribution \u2192 CFS is load balancing properly\n- One core with many more processes \u2192 possible pinning or imbalance\n- Core 0 often has more because boot processes default there\n\n**Context:** The Linux scheduler distributes processes across cores considering NUMA topology, cache locality, and load. A core with 50 processes doesn't mean it's overloaded \u2014 most may be sleeping. Check per-core CPU% for actual load."
    },
    {
      "title": "\ud83d\udd0d Process-to-Core Detail Table (snapshot)",
      "type": "table",
      "datasource": {
        "type": "prometheus",
        "uid": "${DS_PROMETHEUS}"
      },
      "targets": [
        {
          "expr": "bcm_process_core_map",
          "legendFormat": "",
          "datasource": {
            "type": "prometheus",
            "uid": "${DS_PROMETHEUS}"
          },
          "instant": true,
          "range": false,
          "format": "table"
        }
      ],
      "gridPos": {
        "x": 0,
        "y": 30,
        "w": 24,
        "h": 8
      },
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {
          "unit": "",
          "thresholds": {
            "mode": "absolute",
            "steps": [
              {
                "color": "green",
                "value": null
              }
